TY  - JOUR
TI  - Agent-Based Systems for Academic Research Automation
AU  - Smith, John
AU  - Johnson, Sarah
PY  - 2023
AB  - We propose an agent-based framework for automating academic research workflows. The system integrates multiple specialized agents for literature search, screening, data extraction, and synthesis. Each agent operates within strict constraints to ensure traceability and auditability of the research process. Evaluation on 500 research papers shows that the agent system achieves 87% precision in relevant paper identification and 92% accuracy in data extraction tasks, outperforming traditional keyword-based approaches.
JO  - ACM Computing Surveys
DO  - 10.1145/acs.2023.042
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
TI  - Systematic Review Automation Using Natural Language Processing
AU  - Brown, Alice
AU  - Davis, Robert
AU  - Wilson, Emily
AU  - Taylor, Michael
PY  - 2023
AB  - Systematic reviews are essential but time-consuming. We present NLP-SR, a tool that uses natural language processing to semi-automate the systematic review process. The tool assists with study screening, data extraction, and risk of bias assessment. In a comparative evaluation involving three systematic reviews, NLP-SR reduced screening time by 65% while maintaining 95% sensitivity compared to manual screening. The tool implements a human-in-the-loop design to ensure quality control at critical decision points.
JO  - BMC Medical Research Methodology
DO  - 10.1186/bmc.2023.089
ER  - 

TY  - CONF
TI  - Evidence-Grounded Summarization for Academic Papers
AU  - Park, Soo-Jin
AU  - Kim, Hae-Won
PY  - 2024
AB  - We introduce a novel framework for generating evidence-grounded summaries of academic papers. Our approach enforces strict citation constraints, requiring every claim in the summary to be traceable to specific text spans in the source document. Experiments on a curated dataset of 200 papers from multiple domains show that our method reduces unsupported claims by 78% compared to baseline summarization models. The framework also provides an evidence map that links each summary sentence to its source evidence.
JO  - Proceedings of ACL 2024
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
TI  - Automated Boolean Query Generation for Systematic Review Search
AU  - Garcia, Maria
AU  - Martinez, Carlos
PY  - 2022
AB  - Developing effective search strategies is a critical step in systematic reviews. We present an automated approach for generating Boolean queries from research questions using large language models. The system expands seed keywords into comprehensive search terms including synonyms, variants, and exclusion terms, then constructs database-specific Boolean expressions. Evaluation across 50 systematic review topics shows that automated queries achieve 91% recall compared to expert-crafted queries, with significantly reduced development time.
JO  - Information Processing & Management
DO  - 10.1016/ipm.2022.103
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
TI  - Multi-Source Academic Search Integration via Open APIs
AU  - Thompson, David
AU  - Lee, Jennifer
AU  - Anderson, Peter
PY  - 2023
AB  - We present a unified framework for searching and aggregating academic literature from multiple open APIs including OpenAlex, Semantic Scholar, and Crossref. The system handles deduplication, metadata normalization, and quality assessment across heterogeneous sources. Our evaluation demonstrates that combining multiple sources increases unique relevant paper coverage by 34% compared to using any single source alone. The framework implements intelligent rate limiting and caching to ensure compliance with API terms of service.
JO  - Scientometrics
DO  - 10.1007/sci.2023.056
